\section{Tim's Core language}

Tim's verifier works like this.
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Desugaring} (\Cref{sec:tim-core-syntax}) transforms Source Verse into TimCore.
\item \textbf{Ingestion} (\Cref{sec:ingestion}) successively rewrites the TimCore term, keeping its
  structure but:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Augmenting the inferences |G| that are attached to each scope node.
  \item Performing beta reductions
  \end{itemize}
  Only when ingestion has reached a fixpoint do we move on to the next step.
\item \textbf{Inference saturation} (\Cref{sec:inf-sat}) does dominator analysis on each
  inference set |G| separately, and successively rewrites the |G| to reflect the result of this analysis.

\item \textbf{Effect analysis} (\Cref{sec:effect-anal}) checks each sub-term |check fx e| to ensure
  that the effects of |e| are indeed covered by |fx|.
\end{itemize}

Questions:
\begin{itemize}
\item Could inference saturation give rise to new ingestion opportunities?  We think no.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Syntax} \label{sec:tim-core-syntax}

\begin{figure}
$$
\begin{array}{rcll}
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\text{\bf Vertices}} \\
|vt|  & ::= & |x| \vb |tup (x_1, xdots, x_n)| \\
|vv|  & ::= & |vt| \vb |k| \vb |f^[x]| \\
|v|   & ::= & |vv| \vb |lam x e| \\
\\
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\text{\bf Scopes}} \\
|s| & ::= & |scope (x_1, xdots, x_n) G e| \\
\\
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\text{\bf Expressions}} \\
|e| & ::= & |x = vv| \\
    & \vb & |x = timlam h fx i x s_0 j y s_1| \\
%    & \vb & |y=length^[x]| \\
    & \vb & |x = fail| \\
    & \vb & |s_1 `choice` s_2| \\
    & \vb & |e_1 ; e_2| \\
    & \vb & |check fx e|           & \text{Effects check} \\
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\text{Omitting for now: cast, error, in, iterate, next}} \\
\\
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\text{\bf Inferences}} \\
|G| & ::= & |emp| \vb |G, g| \\
|g| & ::= & |edge vt w|  & \text{Data flow from |w| to |v|} \\
    & \vb & |equals S x fail|   & \text{|v| is unified with failure}\\
    & \vb & |equals S x w| & \\
%   & \vb & |lengthis S y z| &  \\
   & \vb & |dominates S vt w| & \text{|w| dominates |v|} \\
\\
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\text{\bf Strengths}} \\
|S,T| & ::= &  |succeeds| \vb |decides| \vb |resolves| \\
\\
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\text{\bf Effects}} \\
|fx| & ::= & S \vb |iterates| \vb |fails| \vb |contradicts| \vb |abstracts|
\end{array}
$$
\caption{Tim Core Verse} \label{fig:tim-core-verse}
\end{figure}

Things to note:
\begin{itemize}
\item A \emph{scope} |scope xs G e| binds some existentials |xs|, has a collection of inferences |G| (initially empty), and wraps an expression |e|.
\item |v| stands for ``vertex'' rather than ``value''.  (The form |f^[x]| isn't really a value.)
\item In a vertex we have an ordinary (POPL) lambda |lam x e|.  Only in an expression do we have a TimLambda.
\item In a TimLambda |timlam h fx i x s_0 j y s_1|:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item |h| is a (bound) occurrence of a variable, presumably already in scope.
  \item |s_0| is called the \emph{domain scope} and |s_1| is the \emph{range scope}.
  \item |i| and |x| are binders, and scope over |s_0| and |s_1|.
  \item |j| and |y| are binders, and scope over |s_1|.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

Questions:
\begin{itemize}
\item In the edge |(edge v w)| isn't the LHS, |v|, always a (flexible) variable?
\item Why |x=fail|?
\item Does |dominates S v w| have a strength? Why?
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Ingestion} \label{sec:ingestion}

\begin{figure}
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\begin{array}{rcl}
X & ::= & |hole| \vb |X ; e| \vb |e ; X|
\end{array}\\
\\
\multicolumn{1}{c}{\large \fbox{
$|scope xs G_1 e_1| \quad \rightarrow \quad |scope xs G_2 e_2|$
}} \\
\\
\begin{array}{lrcll}
\rulename{res} & |scope xs G (X^[x=vv])| & \rightarrow & |scope xs (G,equals resolves x vv) (X^[x=vv])| \\
\end{array}
\end{array}
$$
\caption{Ingestion rules} \label{fig:tim-ingestion}
\end{figure}

\Cref{fig:tim-ingestion} gives the ``ingestion'' rules.  Generally they simply augment the inferences |G|
in (any of) the scope-expression |s| in the program.  Points to note:
\begin{itemize}
\item The context |X| looks inside a nested tree of ``|;|'' compositions; but it does not look inside
  nested scopes or choices.  So only the innermost |G| is affected.
\end{itemize}
\noindent
Questions:
\begin{itemize}
\item To avoid lots of duplication, I used vertices |v| in \rulename{lflex}. But that does not
  account for the POPL-lambda vs Tim-lambda difference between expresions |e| and inferences |g|.
  Maybe \rulename{lflex} would be better written as a G-to-G rewrite
  $$ |xs; equals resolves x v| \; \rightarrow \; |xs; equals resolves x v, edge x v| \quad \text{if $|x| \in |xs|$}$$
\item Beta reduction may not reach a fixpoint.  Ditto iteration?
\item Can \rulename{res} be generalised  |x=v|?
 \end{itemize}

\subsection{Inference saturation} \label{sec:inf-sat}

\newcommand{\satarrow}{\rightarrow^{+}}

\begin{figure}
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\multicolumn{1}{c}{\large \fbox{
$|xs; G_1| \satarrow |G_2|$
}} \\
\multicolumn{1}{c}{\text{Extend |G_1| with new (implied) inferences |G_2|}}
\\ \\
\begin{array}{lrcll}
\rulename{trans} & |xs; G, equals resolves v_1 v_2, equals resolves v_2 v_3| & \satarrow & |equals resolves v_1 v_3| \\
\rulename{lflex} & |xs; G, equals resolves x vv| & \satarrow & |edge x vv| 
     & \text{if $x \in |xs|$} \\
\rulename{rflex} & |xs; G, equals resolves x y| & \satarrow & |edge y x| 
     & \text{if $|y| \in |xs|$} \\
\end{array}
\end{array}
$$
\caption{Inference saturation} \label{fig:infernce-saturation}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Effect analysis} \label{sec:effect-anal}

\begin{figure}
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\multicolumn{1}{c}{\large \fbox{
$|effects G e| = |fx|$
}} \\
\\
\begin{array}{rcll}
  |effects G_1 (scope xs G_2 e)| & = & |effects ((G_1,G_2)) e| \\
  |effects G (e_1 ; e_2)| & = & |andeffects (effects G e_1) (effects G e_2)| \\
  |effects G (x=v)| & = & S & \text{if $|equals S x v| \in |G|$} \\
  |effects G (x=k)| & = & |fails| & \text{if $|equals resolves x k'| \in |G|$ and $k \not= k'$}
\end{array} \\
\\
\multicolumn{1}{c}{\large \fbox{
$|andeffects fx_1 fx_2| = |fx|$
}} \\
\\
\begin{array}{lrcl}
\multicolumn{4}{c}{\text{All equations also apply with arguments swapped, and apply top-to-bottom}} \\
(E1) & |andeffects contradicts fx| & = & |contradicts| \\
(E2) & |andeffects fails fx|       & = & |fails| \\
(E3) & |andeffects succeeds fx|     & = & |fx| \\
(E4) & |andeffects abstracts fx|  & = & |abstracts| \\
(E5) & |andeffects iterates fx|   & = & |iterates| \\
(E6) & |andeffects resolves iterates| & = & |abstracts| \\
(E7) & |andeffects resolves fx|  & = & |resolves| \\
(E8) & |andeffects decides fx|   & = &  |decides|
\end{array}
\end{array}
$$
\caption{Effect analysis} \label{fig:effect-analysis}
\end{figure}
Quesions:
\begin{itemize}
\item E5 wins over E6?
\item Where does |contradicts| come from?
\end{itemize}


